The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Robbers decamp with 6.32 lakh
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     Robbers decamp with 6.32 lakh
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Gaya, May 27: Six motorcycle-borne men looted Rs 6.32 lakh from Gurua branch of the Punjab National Bank today around 11am.        
	The robbers assaulted three bank employees, including the branch manager, Amreshwar Prasad, with revolver butts before with the money and the double-barrel gun of the bank guard.         
	According to reports reaching the district headquarters, the robbers entered the bank premises around 11am and overpowered the guard and snatched his double-barrel gun.         
	Then the bank staff and customers were huddled together and directed to stay quiet. The robbers then looted mobile phones and Rs 6.32 lakh from the bank and came out in an unhurried pace. They subsequently boarded two motorcycles and sped away.         
	The injured employees were given first aid at a local clinic, as they did not require hospitalisation, said a police officer.         
	Raj Vansh Singh, the Gaya police station spokesperson, confirming the incident and said the Gurua police station officer in-charge Rajesh Kumar claimed that the police chased the robbers, but the latter managed to flee.         
	Bank loots have become common in the district in the past few years. Branches of PNB and Madhya Bihar Grameen Bank (earlier known as Magadh Grameen Bank) had been targeted by the robbers several times.                                                                                                                                                                          
